# Help text

testjxMainHelp

"<html>

<head>
<title> Help </title>
</head>

Hey, look!  We finally provide <a href=jxhelp:testjxHyperHelp>
<b>hypertext</b> help</a>!
<p>
Examples of HTML formatting:
<p>
<b>bold</b> <i>italic</i> <tt>fixed width</tt> <font color=red>red</font>
<ul>
<li> unordered list item
<li> another item
</ul>
<ol>
<li> ordered list item
<li> another item
</ol>

</html>"

testjxHyperHelp

"<html>

<head>
<title> Hypertext </title>
</head>

Yes, hypertext help is finally here.  Several types of links are supported:

<ul>
<li> links: <a href=jxhelp:testjxMainHelp>main help page</a>
<li> subsections: <a href=jxhelp:#subsection>the bottom of this text</a>

<p>
<li> URLs: <a href=http://www.newplanetsoftware.com/jx/>JX</a>
<li> email: <a href=mailto:jafl@newplanetsoftware.com>John Lindal</a>

<p>
<li> pointless reference to self: <a href=jxhelp:#>you are here</a>

<p>
<li> link that isn't registered with <tt>JXHelpManager</tt>:
     <a href=jxhelp:unregistered>unregistered</a>

<p>
<li> link that is registered but doesn't have any text:
     <a href=jxhelp:testjxNoTextHelp>no text</a>
</ul>

<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>

<a name=subsection>

<b> This is the bottom of this text. </b>

</html>"

# CBMDIServer
#2345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890123456789012345678901234567890

CommandLineHelp::TestMDIServer

"This X application demonstrates the capabilities of the JX C++ application
framework and GUI class library.

Usage:  <options>

-h            prints help
-v            prints version information
-iconic       start with the main window iconified
-nobuffer     turn off buffered drawing in main window
              (for bragging about optimized redrawing code)
-imagebuffer  buffer drawing in main window by using JXImage
              (bad idea in general because it hogs memory)
-snoopwindow  print message whenever main window is (de)iconified

-MDI          activate Multiple Document Interface
              When an MDI testjx process is already running and you use this
              option, none of the other options are valid, but you can specify
              an arbitrary number of files to open."

